any":"Rubenheim, Gersheim, Saarpfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Duitsland","Rubenheim, Palatinate, Bavaria, Germany":"Pfalz, Bayern, Duitsland","of Rubenheim, Gersheim, Saar, Germany":"Pfalz, Bayern, Duitsland","Rubenheim, Saarpfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Deutschland (damals HRR)":"Rubenheim, Gersheim, Saarpfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Duitsland"},"en":{"1650–5 MAR 1710":"about 1650–5 March 1710","–Male":"Deceased","1650–1695":"about1650–1695","1670–1718":"1670–1718","1674–Female":"1674–Deceased","1674–1757":"1674–1757","1650–1710":"about1650–1710","1710":"1710","Abt 1674":"about 1674","1674":"1674","ABT 1695":"about 1695","1695":"1695","1650":"about 1650","ABT 1670/1675":"from 1670 to 1675","1670":"1670","1718":"1718","5 MAR 1710":"5 March 1710","1757":"1757","Rubenheim,Saarland,Germany":"Rubenheim, Gersheim, Saarpfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Germany","Rubenheim, Palatinate, Bavaria, Germany":"Palatinate, Bavaria, Germany","of Rubenheim, Gersheim, Saar, Germany":"Palatinate, Bavaria, Germany","Rubenheim, Saarpfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Deutschland (damals HRR)":"Rubenheim, Gersheim, Saarpfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Brück","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Naftali, Eliahu, Hershel, Meyer, Ruvim, Shloime, Yoav.","German (also <b>Brück</b>): topographic name for someone who lived near a bridge, or an occupational name for a bridge keeper or toll collector on a bridge, from Middle High German <i>bruck(e)</i> ‘bridge’. <i>Bruck</i> remained the Bavarian and Austrian form, reflected in placenames such as Innsbruck, whereas in central and northern Germany <i>Brück(e)</i> was the regular and ultimately standard form, as for example in the placename <i>Osnabrück</i>. Switzerland has both forms. See also   Brueck  .","Jewish (from Poland and Belarus): from Polish, Belorussian, or Yiddish <i>bruk</i> ‘pavement’, possibly a metonymic occupational name for a paver."],"variants":[{"name":"Brueckman","meanings":["Americanized form of North German <b>Brückmann</b>: variant of   Bruck  , with the addition of <i>-mann</i> ‘man’. Compare   Bruckman  ."]},{"name":"Brueck","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Heinz, Hermann.","German (<b>Brück</b>): see   Bruck  ."]},{"name":"Brucker","meanings":["German (also <b>Brücker</b>): topographic name for someone who lived near a bridge, or an occupational name for a bridge keeper or toll collector on a bridge (see   Bruck  ), or a habitational name for someone from any of numerous places in southern Germany, Austria, and Switzerland named Bruck or Brugg (compare   Brugger  ). Compare also   Bruecker  .","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): occupational name, either from a Yiddishized form of Polish <i>brukarz</i> ‘paver’ or from an agent noun based on Yiddish <i>bruk</i> ‘pavement’.","English (Jersey): variant of   Brooker  ."]},{"name":"Bruk","meanings":["Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of   Bruck   2."]},{"name":"Bruckman","meanings":["Americanized form of South German <b>Bruckmann</b> and North German <b>Brückmann</b>: variant of   Bruck  , with the addition of <i>-mann</i> ‘man’. Compare   Brookman   and   Brueckman  .","English: variant of   Brookman  . This surname is rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Brugge","meanings":["Dutch (<b>Van der Brugge</b>): topographic name for someone living near a <i>brug</i> ‘bridge’.","Flemish and Dutch: habitational name from Bruges.","North German (<b>Brügge</b>): variant of   Bruck   or a habitational name from any of several places called Brügge."]},{"name":"Bruckner","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Albrecht, Arno, Gunther, Hans, Helmut, Juergen, Kurt, Markus, Oskar, Wolfgang.","German (also <b>Brückner</b>): occupational name for someone in charge of a bridge, typically a toll collector; a variant of   Bruck   with the addition of the suffix <i>-ner</i>.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): occupational name for a paver, from Yiddish <i>bruk</i> ‘pavement’ + the agent suffix <i>-ner</i>."]}]},{"name":"Anna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[{"name":"Anne","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."]}]},{"name":"Maria","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Maria  , of German origin but now also moderately popular in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Catherina","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."],"variants":[{"name":"Catheryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Katherine","meanings":["Pet form of   Christopher ;  also of   Katherine   and its variants. In the medieval period it was a pet form of   Christian   and   Christiana ."]},{"name":"Catharin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Catharine","meanings":["Variant spelli